hopobject.body: Thanks for calling demeds.info In the United States, though, only the recession year of 2009 had a larger emissions decline than 2012. The EIA reports that energy consumption fell 2.4% last year, helped partly by a very warm first quarter that lowered heating demand, while energy intensity (energy use per dollar of GDP) rose 5.1%, spurred partly by more fuel-efficient vehicles. It also attributed the emissions decline to a greater substitution in power generation from coal to natural gas, which emits much less carbon dioxide, and greater use of renewable energy such as solar and wind.
